[
  {
    "type": "h1",
    "content": "What is continuity?"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Think of it as being able to draw a graph with a pencil without taking your pencil off the paper. If you can do so, then the graph is continous, otherwise it is discontinuous."
  },
  {
    "type": "h2",
    "content": "Example of a continuous graph"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Following the cursor, it smoothly traces over the function $f(x) = \\sin(x)$, indicating that it is continuous over the domain $ [0,\\ 2\\pi] $."
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "In fact, $ \\sin(x) $ is continuous for all $ [-\\infty, \\ +\\infty] $."
  },
  {
    "type": "video",
    "url": "/videos/lectures/continuous-graph-1.mp4"
  },
  {
    "type": "h2",
    "content": "Example of a discontinuous graph"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "In this animation, you can see how the cursor must \"jump\" from on part of the function to another, which makes it discontinuous."
  },
  {
    "type": "video",
    "url": "/videos/lectures/discontinuous-graph-1.mp4"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "However, do note that the function is continuous from $0$ to $2$ non-inclusive, or $[0, \\ 2)$, and from $2$ inclusive to $+\\infty$, or $[2,\\ +\\infty)$."
  },
  {
    "type": "h1",
    "content": "Types of discontinuities"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "There are 3 types of discontinuities that you should be aware of:"
  },
  {
